CSS = Cascading Style Sheets

- Inline CSS
  <body style="background-color: blue;">
  
- Internal CSS
  <style> 
    body{
      background-color: blue;
    } 
  <styles>
  
  browser default CSS
  https://www.w3schools.com/cssref/css_default_values.asp
  hr: border-style: inset; inset means it makes the line look embedded, none means no height, give it a height
  https://devdocs.io/css/height
  body: display: block;
  
  hr width: px / percentage (change according to browser)
  border-style: dotted, none, none;
  when specify three values, dotted->top, none->left&right, bottom->bottom
  equals:
  border-style:none;
  border-top-style:dotted; (more specific)
  when box has no height, hr background color is useless, use border color instead
  
- External CSS
  <head>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="css/styles.css">
  </head>
  syntax:
  selector{property:value;}
  
- Classes vs IDs
  <img class="bacon" src=.....>
  .bacon{
  }
  <h1 id="heading">
  #heading{
  }
  classes and IDs are more specific, will override general img, h1 tags
  ID should be unique, classes are not
  you can have several classes, id not
  <img class="bacon circular" src=.....>
  .bacon{}
  .circular{}
  
  :hover
